body:
First, get a patch I'm sitting on ready to fix recent issue posted on mailing list.

Then,

subexpr.free_temps must be called in all functions where either subexpr.generate_disposal_code or subexpr.generate_post_assignment_code is called.

free_temps should typically be called on the next line, except in circumstances where generate_disposal_code is called many times in difference branches.

Migrated from http://trac.cython.org/ticket/149

comment_data.body:
@dagss changed **priority** from `critical` to `blocker`
commented

Note that as the ''parent'' nodes must call this in the right way on their ''children'' if the ''child'' is new-temp, this is a nasty bug until this is done all over the board.

Making it a blocker.

It is entirely safe to call it in the new way on old-temp nodes though.

@dagss commented

```
dagss@boksen:~/cython/attempt4$ grep generate_disposal_code -nr Cython/ | grep -v orig | grep -v '~' | grep -v free_temp | wc -l
50
```

So the situation is not hopeless by any means, most of these are very quick to fix.

Comments on my (lack of) proper grep skills accepted.

@dagss commented

Note that things aren't irrevocably broken -- one can likely do
```
NewTempExprNode = ExprNode
```
and things should just work on the old temps (though I won't try it unless it's absolutely necesarry to release).

@dagss changed **description** from

One should probably go through and check that all generate_disposal_code is used in the right way, now that it also frees temps. It can be used more than once (in different C code branches) with decref=True, but should only be used once with free_temp=True).

Making the arguments mandatory, and getting the code to run that way, is a good way of doing this, because it forces us to look at all calls.

Adding another method instead wouldn't help that much -- the idea is that wherever generate_disposal_code is used, temps also now needs to be freed which weren't freed earlier.
